Introduction

For this dataset, I opted to work with data involving the NBA, particularly, player-focused data. This set of data are stats from the 2021-22 season, with very few games having been played. The second dataset involved in this process is a list of each NBA team’s salaries. My intention for choosing basketball data relates to my career aspirations. Over the summer, I had the pleasure of working with the Dallas Mavericks, and they provided me a diverse set of information that I had the freedom to manipulate and find insights from. Unfortunately, my R and general coding skills were not sufficient enough to fully explore all that I would have liked to. However, now having some experience from taking this class, I wanted to go back and explore data that I have a lot of familiarity with. I hope in working with NBA data, I can continue to hone my skills and knowledge for what would contribute to a career involving basketball–perhaps something like analytics or marketing. Through this data, I hope to find some early trends on different players, teams, and eventually carve out some datasets that answer a large question for me: Who should be getting the big bucks and who’s overpaid and underpaid?

First, it’s important to mention part of the process for tidying for this project. For the most part, the two datasets I worked with came in Tidy, so I created examples of long and wide pivots to demonstrate since it was not necessary for the original data sets. There were some details that needed to be cleaned out, and that involved renaming the teams (ex: Atlanta Hawks to ATL) to give common variables between the data sets. The team salaries data had salaries for future seasons, but for this project I just needed information for the 2021-22 season and removed the other years. To clean the players data set, I removed some columns that wouldn’t play a role in any of the calculations or summaries and renamed a column to create common variable names betweent the datasets so that we could join.

The clean_teams set had 30 observations, basically denoting that there are 30 NBA teams, while the clean_player set had 403 observations for the 403 players in the NBA. After a simple left join through the variable “Team”, we checked for distinct variables to see if any data was lost or gained, and the result was 403 distinct observations and 403 observations. We further checked this with anti_join and intersect to find rows, columns, and variables that existed between the datasets and those that were varied between the two.

For data-wrangling, I created a typical function to compute the proportion of NAs within each statistical category; often there are players who don’t attempt a free-throw or 3-pointer and that heavily depends on the position of the player and their role within the team. Centers often are the ones that attempt few free throws and few three-pointers and that’s evident from the data. This function was just to compute the percentages of those NAs. What really interests me is different computations based on position. I took a summarized mean on each numerical column and grouped by position to get a look at the different stats per position. In another future project, we could even look for different correlations through a matrix. I wanted to find the super-star for each team, and based it on points scored. The slice_max of 1 was taken for each team for a total of 30 of the biggest scorers in the NBA currently. The mean age was taken for each team, some are obviously very older for example the Lakers, who are in contention for the championship will opt for veteran players, while smaller teams like the Thunder, Raptors, and Magic often have young players and focus on development. The most complicated computations were towards the bigger idea I wanted to address for this project. I wanted to see through a quantitative lens, how much each player really contributes to their team and their matching salary worth based on their contributions. I first summed each of the total stats for each team to use as a denominator in the computations. Next, each players stats were fractioned over their total team stats to give us a percentage of their contributions to Points, Rebounds, Assists, Minutes Played, and blocks. These 5 percentages were added up to give us the variable Player_Con, or total player contribution, and divided by a total of 5(1.0 for each category), and that final percentage was multiplied by the team’s total salary to get a projected pay for each player. I saw parallels to the real salaries that players were given, superstars are paid more than role players but the gap between the players are far larger in real life.

Plot 1 is a visual of the mean ages calculated earlier. This is the mean age of each of the 30 NBA teams with their players. That includes the LA Lakers, BRK Nets, MIA Heat, MIL Bucks, UTA Jazz, PHO Suns–all teams that had deep playoff runs last year. In the NBA, if you’re not contending for a championship, you’re typically rebuilding, which is denoted by picking up a lot of young talent.
